description.narrative:
Activities under this investment will support the research, development, commercialisation and adoption of new drugs, diagnostics, and other disease prevention and control technologies through Product Development Partnerships (PDPs). PDPs bring together funding agencies, private industry and scientists to develop new products for use in poor-country settings where market incentives alone will not drive product development. The $75 million PDP Fund is the flagship investment of the Health Security Initiative for the Indo-Pacific and aims to strengthen the global response against tuberculosis and malaria, particularly the drug-resistant variants.
Grants of up to $18.75 million over 2018-22 were awarded to the: 

Medicines for Malaria Venture to develop and facilitate the uptake of new antimalarial drugs;

Foundation for Innovative New Diagnostics to accelerate the development and adoption of better diagnostic tools and testing protocols for TB and malaria;

